WEBVTT

1
00:00:21.865 --> 00:00:24.745
With the financial support of
the Russian Federation Ministry of Culture.

2
00:00:25.631 --> 00:00:28.900
The Russian Military-Historical Society.

3
00:00:29.738 --> 00:00:33.883
With the support of
the Ukrainian State Film Agency.

4
00:00:40.489 --> 00:00:44.021
Cinema Foundation of Russia.

5
00:00:51.011 --> 00:00:55.191
New People Film Company.

6
00:01:00.358 --> 00:01:03.220
Yulia Peresild

7
00:01:10.525 --> 00:01:13.462
in a film by Sergei Mokritsky.

8
00:01:20.162 --> 00:01:23.522
<i>Moscow. Vnukovo Airport. 1957.</i>

9
00:02:08.773 --> 00:02:13.918
<b>Battle for Sevastopol.</b>

10
00:02:25.055 --> 00:02:29.655
<i>International Student Assembly. USA. 1942.</i>

11
00:02:33.577 --> 00:02:35.857
Fan Bei. infantry. one year at war.
Eight tanks destroyed.

12
00:02:38.458 --> 00:02:41.978
Nikolai Krasavchenko. head of the
delegation of Soviet students.

13
00:02:42.370 --> 00:02:44.338
Communist.

14
00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:56.179
She's very pleased. And how many
people have you killed?

15
00:02:56.221 --> 00:02:59.341
I'm engaged in party work. inspiring
my comrades to heroic works.

16
00:02:59.582 --> 00:03:00.926
It's vital work.

17
00:03:08.303 --> 00:03:12.383
Vladimir Chelintsev. sniper.
152 killed with 154 bullets.

18
00:03:55.752 --> 00:03:57.103
- Come on. come on!
- Look!

19
00:03:57.145 --> 00:04:01.072
<b>Kiev National University. 1937.</b>

20
00:04:01.993 --> 00:04:03.912
Excuse me. sorry. Can I get through.

21
00:04:03.954 --> 00:04:05.836
Excuse me. please.

22
00:04:06.874 --> 00:04:11.807
Lyuda! Woo! We passed. Me and you passed.
We passed Lyuda! Come on. look!

23
00:04:12.875 --> 00:04:15.594
We got in as well!
Let's go to the park.

24
00:04:15.636 --> 00:04:17.455
- C'mon. Aren't you happy?
- Yeah. I am.

25
00:04:17.497 --> 00:04:19.782
You get soft drinks. I've got the beer.
To the park!

26
00:04:19.824 --> 00:04:21.458
I can't. I need to get home.

27
00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:23.962
- Fine. but we'll be waiting for you.
- You're coming. yeah?

28
00:04:24.004 --> 00:04:26.044
- Come on everyone!
- Make sure you come. okay.

29
00:04:26.086 --> 00:04:27.636
- Race you there!
- <i>Okay... Woo!</i>

30
00:04:27.678 --> 00:04:30.297
<i>- How did those idiots pass?
- What're we gonna do?</i>

31
00:04:30.339 --> 00:04:32.015
<i>Well I'm gonna complain
to the committee!</i>

32
00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:36.560
<b>Department of History</b> <b>1. Pavlichenko. L.M.</b>
<b>2. Baskakov. N.I.</b>

33
00:04:39.121 --> 00:04:41.000
Mom. Mom.

34
00:04:42.121 --> 00:04:44.200
Can I borrow your dress for the day?

35
00:04:44.762 --> 00:04:46.281
Of course.

36
00:04:46.601 --> 00:04:49.202
Thanks. I'll go get changed and then
come back and help you.

37
00:04:53.043 --> 00:04:56.442
So Budarin comes back with:
'The war in Spain has shown us'

38
00:04:56.604 --> 00:04:59.002
'that the era of waving
around swords is over.'

39
00:04:59.044 --> 00:05:02.003
And Vedernikov just loses it. grabs
his sword and starts chasing him.

40
00:05:02.045 --> 00:05:05.285
Lucky that he couldn't catch him.
I'll wait outside for you.

41
00:05:05.445 --> 00:05:06.966
I'll just change and then be with you.

42
00:05:08.606 --> 00:05:10.045
Hello Father.

43
00:05:14.167 --> 00:05:16.085
Well don't you look nice.

44
00:05:16.127 --> 00:05:20.247
At least you're not wearing my army
jacket as well. Pass me my boots.

45
00:05:20.968 --> 00:05:24.248
I passed. top of my class.

46
00:05:24.409 --> 00:05:26.128
Well done. Congratulations.

47
00:05:29.530 --> 00:05:31.489
You could be proud of me.

48
00:05:35.091 --> 00:05:39.691
Misha. try to be gentler with her today.

49
00:05:40.084 --> 00:05:42.571
<i>Not only in our country...</i>

50
00:05:46.253 --> 00:05:49.372
Dad. what time are you back?
Dad?

51
00:05:54.654 --> 00:05:56.414
By dinner. but don't wait for me.

52
00:05:57.295 --> 00:05:59.533
We wanted to invite the neighbours
around to dinner.

53
00:05:59.575 --> 00:06:01.055
to celebrate the good news. with you.

54
00:06:01.097 --> 00:06:05.818
What's to celebrate?
She needed to pass and she passed.

55
00:06:08.017 --> 00:06:09.656
- Well done.
- Come on. help me here.

56
00:06:09.817 --> 00:06:13.578
Father! Promise that you'll come back
a little bit earlier.

57
00:06:19.499 --> 00:06:20.779
Lyuda?

58
00:06:28.701 --> 00:06:33.421
Daddy. come on. higher.
Come on Daddy.

59
00:06:34.022 --> 00:06:38.462
Higher. higher. higher!
Come on Daddy. higher. higher!

60
00:06:38.631 --> 00:06:40.382
One. two. three. four. turn.
and one...

61
00:06:40.783 --> 00:06:42.662
Lyuda! Lyuda!

62
00:06:43.304 --> 00:06:46.023
We're historians now.
We have to strive for the truth.

63
00:06:46.156 --> 00:06:48.277
Cinema lies. the shooting
range is where the truth is.

64
00:06:48.319 --> 00:06:49.332
There's your change.

65
00:06:49.375 --> 00:06:51.560
Your change.
<i>Ladies. how can I help?</i>

66
00:06:51.602 --> 00:06:52.640
Listen. Zahar...

67
00:06:52.682 --> 00:06:55.242
Well. the shooting range doesn't...
it's all done properly there.

68
00:06:55.284 --> 00:06:57.364
I mean. there are real
bullets. real weapons.

69
00:06:57.406 --> 00:06:58.775
- So what?
- Are we going?

70
00:06:58.817 --> 00:07:00.949
Guys. you can even smell
the gunpowder there.

71
00:07:01.387 --> 00:07:04.107
Gunpowder? Why do we
need to smell gunpowder?

72
00:07:04.267 --> 00:07:07.506
So what if cinema isn't reality.
life can still be a fairy tale.

73
00:07:07.548 --> 00:07:09.908
- Plus you promised.
- I'm for the cinema too.

74
00:07:10.069 --> 00:07:13.628
There's passion. and love. and music
which never ends.

75
00:07:13.790 --> 00:07:15.512
- I'm for the shooting range.
- Lyuda?

76
00:07:15.554 --> 00:07:17.389
Oh. so that's three against three.

77
00:07:17.431 --> 00:07:22.550
Hold on. I've got an idea:
Heads is shooting range; Tails. cinema.

78
00:07:22.592 --> 00:07:24.152
Wanna bet the beer that it'll be heads?

79
00:07:24.194 --> 00:07:25.234
I don't want to bet.

80
00:07:30.672 --> 00:07:32.392
- Lyuda. which is it?
- Well?

81
00:07:34.313 --> 00:07:35.393
Heads.

82
00:07:43.275 --> 00:07:45.522
Guys. what're you faffing around for?
Shoot quicker.

83
00:07:45.565 --> 00:07:47.515
We might still be able
to make the cinema.

84
00:07:47.558 --> 00:07:48.133
Aha.

85
00:07:48.154 --> 00:07:50.035
We're not just shooting.
we're having a contest.

86
00:07:50.077 --> 00:07:51.077
Oooh.

87
00:07:51.477 --> 00:07:52.836
I want to shoot too.

88
00:07:54.398 --> 00:07:56.836
Well. you can shoot later.

89
00:07:56.878 --> 00:07:58.716
No. I want to be in the contest.

90
00:07:58.758 --> 00:08:01.331
Yeah. you show them.
You show those film-haters.

91
00:08:01.638 --> 00:08:05.237
Hey Lyudmila. don't worry.
Fourth place is still pretty good.

92
00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:07.760
- Very funny.
- Each of you have five shots.

93
00:08:07.879 --> 00:08:10.639
The winner is determined by
the number of points scored.

94
00:08:13.561 --> 00:08:15.199
Can you show me how?

95
00:08:15.241 --> 00:08:17.960
Pick up the rifle. Load!

96
00:08:20.442 --> 00:08:22.722
Put the cartridges into the magazine.

97
00:08:29.524 --> 00:08:31.043
Fire!

98
00:08:32.364 --> 00:08:33.364
Bullseye!

99
00:08:36.205 --> 00:08:41.365
Line up your rear sight. front sight
and the target.

100
00:08:42.126 --> 00:08:44.766
Breathe steadily.

101
00:08:45.367 --> 00:08:50.727
Then hold your breath and gently put
pressure on the trigger.

102
00:08:50.888 --> 00:08:53.928
And fire.

103
00:09:02.410 --> 00:09:04.209
Weapons on the table.

104
00:09:06.450 --> 00:09:08.331
Weapons on the table.

105
00:09:09.811 --> 00:09:12.131
Call out your surnames loudly and clearly.

106
00:09:12.372 --> 00:09:14.371
- Kolesov.
- Kutzyh.

107
00:09:15.132 --> 00:09:16.250
Feldman.

108
00:09:16.292 --> 00:09:17.492
Pavlichenko.

109
00:09:17.653 --> 00:09:20.693
Pavlichenko's about to see that
shooting is not for women.

110
00:09:20.853 --> 00:09:22.372
We'll see about that.

111
00:09:22.414 --> 00:09:25.293
Look. you couldn't even get one hole
in your target.

112
00:09:26.254 --> 00:09:31.135
The winner is Pavlichenko with
47 out of 50 points.

113
00:09:31.895 --> 00:09:34.167
Commander. are you sure
you checked those right?

114
00:09:34.776 --> 00:09:36.654
Look for yourself if you want.

115
00:09:36.696 --> 00:09:38.576
<i>How many points for Feldman?</i>

116
00:09:39.057 --> 00:09:41.778
Oh Lyuda. it's good that we didn't
go to the cinema after all. right?

117
00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:44.099
<i>Ha! Serves you right!</i>

118
00:09:44.618 --> 00:09:51.258
Every war ends either in peace.
or in armistice.

119
00:09:51.699 --> 00:09:55.659
So. in the year 1651...

120
00:09:56.941 --> 00:09:58.978
- Excuse me.
- It's okay. come in.

121
00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:00.180
Miss Pavlichenko.

122
00:10:02.661 --> 00:10:03.820
Yes.

123
00:10:03.982 --> 00:10:07.901
To the Rector's office please.
and take your things just in case.

124
00:10:08.502 --> 00:10:11.902
<i>And so we continue. After the
so-called Treaty of Bila Tserkva...</i>

125
00:10:13.984 --> 00:10:16.743
Miss Pavlichenko. This way.

126
00:10:25.386 --> 00:10:30.225
Lyudmila Pavlichenko. born in 1916.

127
00:10:30.387 --> 00:10:32.586
Mother. Mrs N.G. Pavlichenko.
English teacher.

128
00:10:32.747 --> 00:10:37.827
and father. M.S. Pavlichenko.
major in the NKVD. Correct?

129
00:10:43.149 --> 00:10:45.869
You write it all down. comrade Rector.

130
00:10:49.511 --> 00:10:50.830
Was that all correct?

131
00:10:53.231 --> 00:10:54.551
Yes.

132
00:10:57.351 --> 00:11:02.112
Disciplined indeed.
He wasn't lying. surprisingly.

133
00:11:06.634 --> 00:11:09.433
According to a report dated June 20
from Mr Kovalchuk.

134
00:11:09.594 --> 00:11:13.034
a shooting instructor at Osovi
Yahimova's firing range.

135
00:11:13.192 --> 00:11:15.273
he witnessed your excellent results.
You have talent.

136
00:11:15.315 --> 00:11:17.475
Hence we have decided to send you
on a six-month course

137
00:11:17.517 --> 00:11:19.725
to teach you precision marksmanship.
Congratulations.

138
00:11:20.316 --> 00:11:21.515
And my studies?

139
00:11:21.557 --> 00:11:25.675
What about them? I think your rector is
also very much in favour.

140
00:11:25.717 --> 00:11:28.958
In six month's time. you come back. and
finish your studies. That's okay isn't it?

141
00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:34.357
Yes. yes. of course. of course.
You come back. and complete your studies.

142
00:11:34.399 --> 00:11:35.478
Okay.

143
00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:40.119
Do I have a choice in this?

144
00:11:46.561 --> 00:11:48.960
I wouldn't advise it.

145
00:11:49.842 --> 00:11:52.642
- Honey. at least take a sweater.
- Mom. they give us everything there.

146
00:11:52.684 --> 00:11:55.881
And what if they don't? Besides. you'll
need something until you get there.

147
00:11:55.923 --> 00:11:58.761
Here's some pierogi. You won't be
able to get mom's pirogi there.

148
00:11:58.803 --> 00:12:00.608
Don't you want to say anything to me?

149
00:12:01.804 --> 00:12:05.643
Oh God! Well. it is for six months.
Misha. it's the middle of winter...

150
00:12:05.685 --> 00:12:08.284
Can't you just call them
and have it postponed?

151
00:12:08.565 --> 00:12:10.204
Lyuda!

152
00:12:27.409 --> 00:12:29.847
All her life you treated her like a boy.

153
00:12:29.889 --> 00:12:31.688
See how that ended up?

154
00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:33.449
Why didn't you stop her?

155
00:12:34.891 --> 00:12:39.570
Half my life I've been at war.
and women get the worst of it.

156
00:12:40.532 --> 00:12:42.490
Soon there will be a new war.

157
00:12:43.652 --> 00:12:46.371
We are. of course. thankful to America...

158
00:12:46.413 --> 00:12:48.371
<b>International Student Assembly. USA. 1942</b>

159
00:12:48.533 --> 00:12:49.910
for the Lend-Lease programme.

160
00:12:49.952 --> 00:12:54.892
But if we want to finish off Hitler
as quickly as possible.

161
00:12:54.934 --> 00:12:58.654
then you need to make a decisive step.

162
00:12:59.015 --> 00:13:03.414
And so the Soviet delegation is asking
you to include the issue...

163
00:13:03.456 --> 00:13:07.215
of opening a second front...

164
00:13:07.376 --> 00:13:09.456
on the assembly's agenda today as
the main item.

165
00:13:32.541 --> 00:13:37.421
The Soviet people need help. they
do not need charity.

166
00:13:37.662 --> 00:13:40.941
That is why. in the name
of the Soviet delegation.

167
00:13:41.823 --> 00:13:43.862
I ask you to stop this farce.

168
00:14:02.707 --> 00:14:04.266
Lyuda. speak!

169
00:14:05.388 --> 00:14:06.667
Pavlichenko!

170
00:15:29.243 --> 00:15:30.922
How come you ended up here?

171
00:15:30.964 --> 00:15:33.164
We've been doing this all summer.
Is this our lives now.

172
00:15:33.206 --> 00:15:34.804
<b>Odessa. June 1941.</b>

173
00:15:34.964 --> 00:15:36.852
As historians. I thought
we'd be excavating

174
00:15:36.894 --> 00:15:39.003
places like Troy and
investigating burial sites.

175
00:15:39.045 --> 00:15:41.645
But what are we supposed to excavate here?

176
00:15:42.206 --> 00:15:44.605
Look at us. like. it's horrific.

177
00:15:45.406 --> 00:15:47.646
Miss Slavochka. Your materials are ready.

178
00:15:50.527 --> 00:15:52.685
Here you go.

179
00:15:52.727 --> 00:15:56.046
- Come back on Monday. Take care.
- Thank you.

180
00:15:56.088 --> 00:15:59.688
Lyuda. do you like sailors?

181
00:16:00.009 --> 00:16:01.648
I like police officers.

182
00:16:02.009 --> 00:16:04.529
The police? Why?

183
00:16:05.250 --> 00:16:07.491
Because if you don't start studying.
I'm gonna call them.

184
00:16:07.533 --> 00:16:09.733
Our exams are just around the corner.
you need to focus.

185
00:16:09.775 --> 00:16:12.775
Still. a sailor would be nice.

186
00:16:14.372 --> 00:16:17.851
I would wait for him. I would...

187
00:16:18.973 --> 00:16:21.052
Then perhaps you should go to the beach.

188
00:16:21.453 --> 00:16:26.133
There's sailors aplenty there. and airmen.
and criminals.

189
00:16:26.294 --> 00:16:29.614
and even police officers.
A fine selection.

190
00:16:29.775 --> 00:16:31.134
See Lyuda. policemen.

191
00:16:35.296 --> 00:16:38.814
Ah Sonya. Sonya. they don't understand.

192
00:16:38.856 --> 00:16:40.816
They just don't listen.

193
00:16:41.216 --> 00:16:43.776
It's Friday. I need to close the library.

194
00:16:43.938 --> 00:16:46.136
Don't worry. I understand you.

195
00:16:46.298 --> 00:16:48.616
I've got other things to do as well.

196
00:16:48.658 --> 00:16:50.017
Yes. yes. yes. yes.

197
00:16:53.099 --> 00:16:58.619
Sonya. tell me. who do you like more.
sailors or airmen?

198
00:16:58.780 --> 00:17:01.338
- Y'know what. go for a doctor. Lyuda.
- Where?

199
00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:04.540
I'm heading off to the beach now.

200
00:17:04.741 --> 00:17:07.579
My brother Boris is going to be there.
He's a doctor.

201
00:17:07.621 --> 00:17:08.701
Is he cute?

202
00:17:08.862 --> 00:17:10.703
He always dreamed of becoming a pilot
as a boy.

203
00:17:10.745 --> 00:17:12.661
Now I want a doctor. Let's go.

204
00:17:12.703 --> 00:17:14.181
But...

205
00:17:14.223 --> 00:17:17.423
Lyuda. if you bury us away here.
soon we'll be turning into Mendel.

206
00:17:17.864 --> 00:17:20.463
Lyuda. you do need to learn to relax.

207
00:17:23.785 --> 00:17:26.905
Fine. We'll continue on Monday.
First thing in the morning!

208
00:17:27.065 --> 00:17:29.664
Yep. From the crack of dawn.

209
00:17:29.706 --> 00:17:33.106
What d'ya think Lyuda. after surgery.
Dr Hoffman himself said.

210
00:17:33.267 --> 00:17:37.266
'Boris. you have hands of gold.'

211
00:17:37.627 --> 00:17:39.426
I mean. you understand what he said right?

212
00:17:39.468 --> 00:17:42.066
He said that my Boris was gifted.

213
00:17:42.108 --> 00:17:45.827
Soon he'll be heading off to Kiev.
and maybe even to Moscow.

214
00:17:45.869 --> 00:17:46.869
Sit down!

215
00:17:47.310 --> 00:17:49.829
- Lyuda. that was a one time thing.
- What was?

216
00:17:49.989 --> 00:17:51.418
Sunstroke. Sit down Maria.

217
00:17:51.460 --> 00:17:54.830
Yes. yes. yes. Go! Sit down!
Lyuda. what if there's a war?

218
00:17:54.991 --> 00:17:56.590
Everyone's saying there will be.

219
00:18:03.712 --> 00:18:05.271
Ladies. hey.

220
00:18:05.313 --> 00:18:07.191
- Really sorry.
- Our sincerest apologies.

221
00:18:07.233 --> 00:18:09.232
We're so sorry. it was an accident.

222
00:18:09.274 --> 00:18:11.551
Let us make it up to you. please.

223
00:18:11.593 --> 00:18:14.592
It's okay. Maria's forgiven you.
and forgotten. You can go boys.

224
00:18:14.634 --> 00:18:15.793
- <i>Come on.</i>
- One sec.

225
00:18:15.944 --> 00:18:17.465
Maria. very pleased to meet you. Greg.

226
00:18:17.507 --> 00:18:18.977
And I'm Nikolai.

227
00:18:20.955 --> 00:18:22.595
What are you reading?

228
00:18:22.756 --> 00:18:24.915
- Hurry up!
- Hey! Come on!

229
00:18:25.276 --> 00:18:28.796
First we'll win our game. then we'll
come back to celebrate our victory.

230
00:18:32.758 --> 00:18:34.157
Come on.

231
00:18:35.878 --> 00:18:37.118
Maria...

232
00:18:39.399 --> 00:18:42.759
Lyuda. who did you like more?
Nik or Greg?

233
00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:44.719
I didn't even notice them.

234
00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:46.799
So notice.

235
00:18:59.763 --> 00:19:00.842
Sonya!

236
00:19:04.163 --> 00:19:05.363
Boris!

237
00:19:08.724 --> 00:19:10.123
- Hello.
- This is Maria.

238
00:19:10.165 --> 00:19:13.084
- Everyone. this is my brother Boris.
- Hello.

239
00:19:13.126 --> 00:19:14.683
Maria. we're going swimming.

240
00:19:14.725 --> 00:19:17.525
<i>Attention. danger.
please swim back at once.</i>

241
00:19:18.246 --> 00:19:19.405
Can I sit?

242
00:19:19.447 --> 00:19:21.286
- Yes.
- Thanks.

243
00:19:23.208 --> 00:19:25.046
I recognised you at once.

244
00:19:26.328 --> 00:19:29.967
And what do you... What did Sonya
tell you about me?

245
00:19:31.529 --> 00:19:34.043
She said that I should
shave. wear some

246
00:19:34.085 --> 00:19:37.089
cologne. iron my trousers
and polish my shoes.

247
00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:40.211
Then to speak to you on the beach and make
a good impression.

248
00:19:40.530 --> 00:19:41.730
That's all?

249
00:19:43.691 --> 00:19:47.331
No. she also said that I should take a
look at you in your bathing suit.

250
00:19:47.532 --> 00:19:49.331
and realise that I need
to marry you at once.

251
00:19:51.013 --> 00:19:52.212
And did you realise?

252
00:19:53.653 --> 00:19:54.812
Boris.

253
00:19:58.574 --> 00:19:59.773
Lyudmila.

254
00:20:02.975 --> 00:20:05.575
- Well. if we're being serious. then...
- They're pilots!

255
00:20:06.015 --> 00:20:07.495
I need time to decide.

256
00:20:12.857 --> 00:20:16.017
Yes. a very interesting book Lyuda.

257
00:20:16.897 --> 00:20:19.417
Ah. so it's Lyuda?
Pleased to meet you.

258
00:20:19.898 --> 00:20:21.538
- Lyudmila.
- Maria.

259
00:20:21.698 --> 00:20:24.658
As we promised. we'd like to invite
you to celebrate our victory with us.

260
00:20:25.339 --> 00:20:28.139
Since he's here. the young gentleman
can also join us.

261
00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:31.138
I can't agree with you there.

262
00:20:31.180 --> 00:20:33.178
How can you be against war?

263
00:20:33.220 --> 00:20:35.541
War is the only thing that can create
justice in the world.

264
00:20:35.583 --> 00:20:37.582
And we. we're the ones who bring it about.

265
00:20:37.901 --> 00:20:40.341
No. Your opinion is very popular these
days. I know.

266
00:20:40.502 --> 00:20:43.261
- Yes.
- But I've never believed that.

267
00:20:43.983 --> 00:20:47.542
Anyway. you're getting worked up for
nothing. There's not going to be a war.

268
00:20:47.584 --> 00:20:53.303
Really? Because my sources higher up
tell me war has already begun.

269
00:20:53.465 --> 00:20:57.184
You're just too afraid to admit it.
That's your weakness.

270
00:20:57.345 --> 00:20:59.945
- Why?
- Because you're a coward.

271
00:21:00.426 --> 00:21:03.786
You want others to defend your family.
your country. your woman.

272
00:21:03.946 --> 00:21:06.346
Now you. can you defend anyone?

273
00:21:06.707 --> 00:21:10.426
Defend... no. but I save people.

274
00:21:13.188 --> 00:21:15.186
I propose a toast.

275
00:21:15.228 --> 00:21:17.587
Let's raise a glass to...

276
00:21:17.629 --> 00:21:19.869
to the ball. The ball which
landed so fortunately.

277
00:21:20.029 --> 00:21:21.508
Very fortunately.

278
00:21:21.550 --> 00:21:23.191
- To the ball. to the ball.
- To the ball.

279
00:21:24.470 --> 00:21:26.789
Lyudmila. have you ever flown in a plane?

280
00:21:26.831 --> 00:21:28.109
Unfortunately not.

281
00:21:28.151 --> 00:21:29.910
Well. on Sunday we've got training flights-

282
00:21:30.072 --> 00:21:32.310
Thank you very much Nikolai. for Sunday.

283
00:21:32.352 --> 00:21:35.230
Boris. didn't you want to invite
Lyuda and Maria to our house too.

284
00:21:35.272 --> 00:21:38.472
Hmm? Dinner? Don't just stand there.

285
00:21:38.591 --> 00:21:39.911
The girls are almost flying away.

286
00:21:39.953 --> 00:21:42.873
Sonya. I'm sorry. but I'd really
like to go flying.

287
00:21:43.434 --> 00:21:47.578
Lyudmila. are you gonna follow
Maria's example and come flying?

288
00:21:47.715 --> 00:21:49.434
<i>Hey Gregory. do I get a parachute?</i>

289
00:21:52.876 --> 00:21:56.116
So that means that you're the only child?

290
00:21:56.636 --> 00:21:57.796
Yes.

291
00:21:58.436 --> 00:22:03.636
So where do you live in Kiev?
Do you have an apartment. a house?

292
00:22:03.678 --> 00:22:05.756
- An apartment.
- A communal one?

293
00:22:05.798 --> 00:22:06.957
No. it's ours.

294
00:22:07.118 --> 00:22:09.198
How many rooms?

295
00:22:09.519 --> 00:22:10.837
- Three.
- And-

296
00:22:10.879 --> 00:22:13.118
The ceilings are 2.9 metres high.
parquet flooring.

297
00:22:13.160 --> 00:22:16.519
fourth storey and it has large windows.
And a telephone.

298
00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:18.959
Why are you asking such nonsense?

299
00:22:19.121 --> 00:22:20.879
Yuzik. this isn't nonsense.

300
00:22:20.921 --> 00:22:26.001
Lyudmila. tell us. have... have you thought
about how many children you'd like to have?

301
00:22:26.722 --> 00:22:32.730
How many boys? And generally what are the
qualities you look for in a husband?

302
00:22:32.883 --> 00:22:36.282
Would he support you. or is it more
important that he love you?

303
00:22:36.324 --> 00:22:38.083
Mom. Dad. don't interrogate our guest.

304
00:22:38.244 --> 00:22:39.842
It's alright. I'm fine.

305
00:22:39.884 --> 00:22:41.443
I haven't really thought about it.

306
00:22:41.485 --> 00:22:42.964
The fish is almost ready.

307
00:22:43.886 --> 00:22:46.365
So what do you think about our Boris?

308
00:22:46.565 --> 00:22:47.685
I don't really know him.

309
00:22:47.846 --> 00:22:51.272
Well then. let me tell you about him.
Boris has always been a big problem for us.

310
00:22:51.315 --> 00:22:52.651
He was such a excellent boy.

311
00:22:52.694 --> 00:22:55.786
You know. everything we could find in
Odessa. we took and crammed into him.

312
00:22:55.829 --> 00:22:58.106
Guess what he got at school?
He received a gold medal.

313
00:22:58.148 --> 00:23:01.046
And do you know how hard the entrance exam
is for medicine in Odessa?

314
00:23:01.088 --> 00:23:03.083
Do you know what Dr
Hoffman says about him?

315
00:23:03.126 --> 00:23:04.530
That he has hands of gold.

316
00:23:04.649 --> 00:23:06.929
Yuzik. see. he's already famous in Kiev.

317
00:23:07.089 --> 00:23:09.528
But none of this is important.

318
00:23:09.570 --> 00:23:14.290
My son can make the person by his side
very happy.

319
00:23:14.771 --> 00:23:17.890
And when he meets that woman. he will
give her a ring.

320
00:23:18.292 --> 00:23:21.212
Boris! Get the ring to
show Lyudmila please.

321
00:23:22.493 --> 00:23:27.891
Lyudmila. you shouldn't expect the earth.
The ring isn't particularly valuable.

322
00:23:27.933 --> 00:23:29.973
- No. it's not even gold.
- <i>You know. on the day...</i>

323
00:23:30.015 --> 00:23:31.296
<i>when Yuzik gave this ring to me.</i>

324
00:23:31.338 --> 00:23:32.778
<i>he was higher up than José de Ribas.</i>

325
00:23:32.820 --> 00:23:34.936
<i>Well. it is still treasured by our family.</i>

326
00:23:35.095 --> 00:23:36.895
<i>Sonya. astonishingly. has made
the fried fish.</i>

327
00:23:36.937 --> 00:23:40.215
- Dad!
- That reminds me of a funny story.

328
00:23:40.376 --> 00:23:43.255
Well. there was this Jewish family and
the grandfather is dying.

329
00:23:43.414 --> 00:23:46.294
He's lying on the couch and about
to breathe his last when a boy runs in.

330
00:23:46.336 --> 00:23:47.656
He says. 'Sonny. come to me.'

331
00:23:47.817 --> 00:23:50.857
The grandmother meanwhile. she's in kitchen
cooking fried fish.

332
00:23:51.018 --> 00:23:54.178
and its smell is filling the room.
He says. 'Please bring me a piece.'

333
00:23:54.339 --> 00:23:56.459
So off the boy Fima runs.
then he comes back and says:

334
00:23:56.501 --> 00:23:59.029
'Grandma said that you
know this is for later.'

335
00:23:59.860 --> 00:24:01.299
You get it?

336
00:24:07.661 --> 00:24:09.420
You understand now. right?

337
00:24:10.221 --> 00:24:13.301
You're laughing? That won't last long.

338
00:24:13.702 --> 00:24:15.421
Turn on the radio. it's started.

339
00:24:15.463 --> 00:24:17.742
What's started? Tell us.

340
00:24:19.223 --> 00:24:21.250
<i>Has authorised me to
issue the following</i>

341
00:24:21.292 --> 00:24:23.622
<i>statement. Today. at 4
o'clock in the morning.</i>

342
00:24:23.664 --> 00:24:25.650
<i>without addressing any
grievances to the Soviet.</i>

343
00:24:25.692 --> 00:24:27.383
<i>Union. and without a
declaration of war.</i>

344
00:24:27.425 --> 00:24:30.064
<i>German forces fell on our country.</i>

345
00:24:30.226 --> 00:24:32.715
<i>and attacked our frontiers
in many places...</i>

346
00:24:32.757 --> 00:24:34.265
See. what did I tell you.

347
00:24:34.666 --> 00:24:37.105
- <i>Zhitomir. Kiev. Sevastopol...</i>
- So that's it then?

348
00:24:37.267 --> 00:24:40.027
<i>Kaunas and some others. killing and
wounding over two hundred persons.</i>

349
00:24:40.069 --> 00:24:46.227
No. that's not it.
Hitler has his plans. and we have ours.

350
00:24:46.388 --> 00:24:50.387
Boris. your mother and I insist that you
take Lyuda to the theatre.

351
00:24:50.429 --> 00:24:52.309
They're performing 'La Traviata'.

352
00:24:52.702 --> 00:24:54.584
<i>Were made from Romanian
and Finnish territory.</i>

353
00:25:00.191 --> 00:25:03.430
<i>That pact was a huge mistake.
All it did was give the Germans</i>

354
00:25:03.472 --> 00:25:07.351
<i>time to mobilise against us. We should
have declared war on them</i>

355
00:25:07.512 --> 00:25:08.591
<i>back in September '39.</i>

356
00:25:08.633 --> 00:25:11.312
<i>But how could we have known that?
I'm not sure it'd have helped.</i>

357
00:25:13.994 --> 00:25:16.392
- <i>It means the Germans are determined.</i>
- I don't think so.

358
00:25:16.434 --> 00:25:18.272
Stop being so pessimistic.

359
00:25:18.314 --> 00:25:20.273
- They're safe there. trust me.
- I don't.

360
00:25:23.915 --> 00:25:25.515
What about your father?

361
00:25:28.356 --> 00:25:29.795
Let's go. or we'll be late.

362
00:25:46.520 --> 00:25:50.160
Lyuda. you really don't need to do this.

363
00:25:54.722 --> 00:25:57.401
The war. Lyudmila. it's no place for women.

364
00:25:58.762 --> 00:26:00.681
The war. Boris. is no place for cowards.

365
00:26:00.723 --> 00:26:02.321
Will you please be quiet!

366
00:26:16.806 --> 00:26:19.869
Lyuda! Lyuda.

367
00:26:20.070 --> 00:26:21.405
You're going to get killed.

368
00:26:23.007 --> 00:26:25.086
I'm a doctor. I can get you an exemption.

369
00:26:25.487 --> 00:26:28.687
You must understand. you really shouldn't
get involved in all this. You should...

370
00:26:28.729 --> 00:26:30.849
You're probably right Boris.

371
00:26:32.928 --> 00:26:35.608
But Father says that I must.

372
00:26:36.529 --> 00:26:39.609
Anyway. I can't just stand on the sidelines
and do nothing. it's shameful.

373
00:26:40.210 --> 00:26:43.650
And what about you? Could you stand it?

374
00:26:45.931 --> 00:26:47.730
I'm more useful here.

375
00:26:48.972 --> 00:26:51.851
We should all do what we do best.

376
00:26:54.573 --> 00:26:58.012
Yes. and I have my course in precision
shooting to finish.

377
00:26:59.253 --> 00:27:00.973
That's where I'm more useful.

378
00:27:03.414 --> 00:27:05.894
And you Boris. go. go to the opera.

379
00:27:12.216 --> 00:27:13.895
Lyuda. Lyuda!

380
00:27:33.300 --> 00:27:34.779
Even the lights here are strange.

381
00:27:34.941 --> 00:27:36.980
<b>USSR Embassy. USA. 1942.</b>

382
00:27:37.181 --> 00:27:41.380
My homeland is at war. and here
the people are only interested

383
00:27:41.422 --> 00:27:45.101
in what underwear I wear. and if
I use lipstick or not.

384
00:27:47.503 --> 00:27:49.902
Lyuda. can you explain what this is about?

385
00:27:58.922 --> 00:28:01.363
What were you whispering about in English
with the First Lady?

386
00:28:01.405 --> 00:28:03.544
- Nikolai.
- What were you colluding about?

387
00:28:03.586 --> 00:28:05.007
Can you explain calmly?

388
00:28:08.586 --> 00:28:14.226
Mrs Eleanor Roosevelt has invited Miss
Pavlichenko to reside in the White House

389
00:28:14.268 --> 00:28:16.866
for the duration of her stay in
the United States.

390
00:28:16.908 --> 00:28:20.188
The invitation is for
Miss Pavlichenko alone.

391
00:28:21.589 --> 00:28:23.909
Did you have any kind of special
instructions about this?

392
00:28:24.069 --> 00:28:27.549
Before now. no Soviet citizen has
ever stayed in the White House unless

393
00:28:27.710 --> 00:28:29.790
part of a delegation.

394
00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:32.710
I don't have to go.

395
00:28:40.593 --> 00:28:43.471
<i>We should grab hold of any opportunity.</i>

396
00:28:43.513 --> 00:28:45.913
Many important issues are dealt with in the
President's home.

397
00:28:45.955 --> 00:28:48.194
It's better that we have someone there.

398
00:28:56.475 --> 00:28:57.515
Fine.

399
00:29:01.076 --> 00:29:04.676
Well then Miss Pavlichenko.

400
00:29:05.558 --> 00:29:07.156
maybe you should decide yourself.

401
00:30:15.051 --> 00:30:16.810
<i>Go! Go!</i>

402
00:30:16.964 --> 00:30:18.645
<b>Marksmanship Training Ground. Summer 1941.</b>

403
00:30:18.687 --> 00:30:20.490
The most important thing for a sniper is

404
00:30:20.532 --> 00:30:22.651
to get to their position unnoticed.

405
00:30:23.132 --> 00:30:25.771
To do this. you need to crawl properly
using your elbows.

406
00:30:25.933 --> 00:30:27.691
- Get your ass lower. lower.
- Lower!

407
00:30:27.733 --> 00:30:30.411
Left leg. rifle. right leg.

408
00:30:30.453 --> 00:30:33.012
Slide! Slide. don't scramble.

409
00:30:33.054 --> 00:30:35.133
Hand on strap. use your feet.

410
00:30:35.257 --> 00:30:37.351
Keep your head down. Quickly!
Quickly! Quickly!

411
00:30:37.394 --> 00:30:38.479
You're dead!

412
00:30:38.522 --> 00:30:41.776
A nice round ass is an
excellent target for an enemy.

413
00:30:43.295 --> 00:30:44.975
<i>Knees. elbows!</i>

414
00:30:45.417 --> 00:30:47.297
<i>Aren't you listening?
Arms closer to the ground!</i>

415
00:30:49.937 --> 00:30:50.937
Sergeant Major!

416
00:31:00.859 --> 00:31:03.259
And how will this help you to
fight a war?

417
00:31:06.220 --> 00:31:07.819
Why are you laughing?

418
00:31:10.461 --> 00:31:14.300
I see that it's not clear to anybody here
that the Germans have taken Zhytomyr

419
00:31:14.342 --> 00:31:19.022
and Riga and have marched on Kiev
and Leningrad!

420
00:31:21.103 --> 00:31:23.622
We believed that the war would be easy.

421
00:31:23.783 --> 00:31:26.823
and would deliver us a quick victory.
But we are on the retreat.

422
00:31:27.264 --> 00:31:31.663
Understand? We're retreating!
And suffering huge casualties!

423
00:31:31.705 --> 00:31:34.344
And tomorrow. those casualties will be you!

424
00:31:34.506 --> 00:31:35.825
And you!

425
00:31:37.706 --> 00:31:41.986
Anything non-regulation. burn it.
Now!

426
00:32:02.471 --> 00:32:04.631
<i>Wider step!</i>

427
00:32:05.352 --> 00:32:07.223
<i>Come on. put some effort in.</i>

428
00:32:08.640 --> 00:32:09.640
<i>Faster!</i>

429
00:32:13.393 --> 00:32:14.512
Come on!

430
00:32:20.074 --> 00:32:21.674
Dig deeper! Deeper!

431
00:32:22.914 --> 00:32:26.513
Asses down! Get your ass down!

432
00:32:26.555 --> 00:32:28.235
<i>Let's see some pace soldiers!</i>

433
00:32:42.838 --> 00:32:44.157
About turn!

434
00:32:45.719 --> 00:32:47.558
<i>Report the differences.</i>

435
00:32:49.520 --> 00:32:52.039
- One rock disappeared.
- A cross has gone too.

436
00:32:52.720 --> 00:32:55.479
The haystack shifted five metres
to the left.

437
00:32:55.521 --> 00:32:57.240
The mound switched places with the stump.

438
00:32:57.961 --> 00:32:59.080
Is that everything?

439
00:32:59.122 --> 00:33:02.800
The stone moved to the right. by a metre.

440
00:33:02.842 --> 00:33:03.953
Not bad.

441
00:33:03.995 --> 00:33:05.242
About turn!

442
00:33:09.523 --> 00:33:10.802
<i>Tighten the locking mechanism.</i>

443
00:33:12.044 --> 00:33:14.283
<i>Faster! Faster! Faster!</i>

444
00:33:14.924 --> 00:33:16.395
<b>Camouflage appearance.</b>

445
00:33:21.245 --> 00:33:24.245
No good. Move it further across.

446
00:33:24.807 --> 00:33:26.726
Yep. that's right.

447
00:33:38.289 --> 00:33:39.289
Dead.

448
00:33:41.529 --> 00:33:43.889
Interesting. but not effective.

449
00:33:45.490 --> 00:33:47.769
<i>Meticulous concealment is essential</i>

450
00:33:47.931 --> 00:33:50.210
<i>for the survival of a sniper.</i>

451
00:33:52.732 --> 00:33:53.843
Dead.

452
00:33:54.460 --> 00:33:56.531
Wrong flowers for this meadow.

453
00:34:11.015 --> 00:34:12.815
Sir. you're dead.

454
00:34:14.055 --> 00:34:16.055
So when does the shooting start?

455
00:34:29.331 --> 00:34:31.290
<i>Steady. steady!</i>

456
00:34:36.091 --> 00:34:37.571
<i>Close the tailgate.</i>

457
00:34:49.262 --> 00:34:51.183
One. two. three.

458
00:34:52.143 --> 00:34:55.023
One. two. three.

459
00:34:59.824 --> 00:35:01.745
One. two. three.

460
00:35:02.225 --> 00:35:04.184
- Pavlichenko.
- Here.

461
00:35:04.985 --> 00:35:08.025
- Do you still want to shoot?
- Yes Sir!

462
00:35:08.946 --> 00:35:10.066
You sure?

463
00:35:12.379 --> 00:35:13.546
I'm sure.

464
00:35:18.788 --> 00:35:20.027
To your position!

465
00:35:26.870 --> 00:35:28.708
Comrade Major. aren't you going to move?

466
00:35:28.750 --> 00:35:30.005
Shoot.

467
00:35:30.574 --> 00:35:33.269
You're a sniper. not the artillery.

468
00:35:45.673 --> 00:35:49.153
Nine points.
Not bad for a beginner.

469
00:35:49.593 --> 00:35:52.194
First five to the firing
line and in position.

470
00:35:52.874 --> 00:35:55.434
Everyone shoots two units of ammunition.

471
00:36:00.875 --> 00:36:02.315
Good afternoon Sir.

472
00:36:03.756 --> 00:36:05.195
<i>Where? To the commander?</i>

473
00:36:14.318 --> 00:36:16.438
Take the assholes. sure.
but leave the girls.

474
00:36:17.279 --> 00:36:18.959
They're not ready yet.

475
00:36:19.992 --> 00:36:23.319
They haven't started shooting yet.
the ammunition's only just arrived.

476
00:36:23.800 --> 00:36:26.038
They've all completed the
marksmanship course.

477
00:36:26.080 --> 00:36:27.960
That's six months' shooting there.

478
00:36:34.042 --> 00:36:35.520
Pity.

479
00:36:35.562 --> 00:36:37.121
It's the same for me.

480
00:36:39.243 --> 00:36:41.483
Less than half of them left.

481
00:36:41.923 --> 00:36:42.963
Listen.

482
00:36:44.804 --> 00:36:46.804
there's this one girl.

483
00:36:47.444 --> 00:36:49.004
look after her.

484
00:36:49.565 --> 00:36:53.045
She'll make a better soldier than
you one day. Pavlichenko will.

485
00:36:54.686 --> 00:36:57.246
<i>Over here. come on.</i>

486
00:36:59.407 --> 00:37:02.887
<b>Odessa. September 1941.</b>

487
00:37:03.047 --> 00:37:07.806
<i>Come on. faster! The Germans aren't gonna
wait for you to finish!</i>

488
00:37:07.848 --> 00:37:10.488
Remember. don't let them get close.

489
00:37:10.889 --> 00:37:13.247
The second you see an
officer. take the shot.

490
00:37:13.289 --> 00:37:16.049
Kill the commander and I reckon you
can take down half the squad.

491
00:37:16.570 --> 00:37:18.050
And don't waste your ammo. Questions?

492
00:37:18.092 --> 00:37:19.812
We've got tanks. Comrade Captain.

493
00:37:23.892 --> 00:37:26.851
A tank can be stopped two ways.

494
00:37:27.372 --> 00:37:31.092
Number one. bombard it with grenades from
a close distance.

495
00:37:32.453 --> 00:37:33.692
And the second?

496
00:37:33.854 --> 00:37:37.053
That's to hit the viewing port of the tank
with armour-piercing bullets.

497
00:37:37.214 --> 00:37:40.654
two shots in exactly the same spot.

498
00:37:41.454 --> 00:37:44.974
That'll break the glass. then you need
a third shot to take out the driver.

499
00:37:45.016 --> 00:37:46.295
Understood.

500
00:37:50.096 --> 00:37:53.536
Comrade Captain. do I get the
armour-piercing rounds?

501
00:38:06.179 --> 00:38:07.179
Airstrike!

502
00:38:07.340 --> 00:38:08.579
<i>Take cover!</i>

503
00:38:58.830 --> 00:39:02.668
<i>Tank! Stay calm men!
Let them get closer.</i>

504
00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:04.350
<i>Wait! Hold back!</i>

505
00:40:17.892 --> 00:40:22.125
Lyuda!

506
00:40:29.486 --> 00:40:31.806
<i>Cover the left flank!</i>

507
00:41:15.575 --> 00:41:19.815
<i>[German] Come on! Forward!</i>

508
00:41:53.103 --> 00:41:56.702
You wounded? Where are you wounded?
You're bleeding.

509
00:42:06.104 --> 00:42:08.825
Take this. Alcohol.

510
00:42:44.432 --> 00:42:45.432
Wait here!

511
00:42:46.736 --> 00:42:49.897
In recognition of the destruction of a
tank during battle. General-Major Petrov.

512
00:42:49.939 --> 00:42:51.431
Commander of the 25th Rifle Division.

513
00:42:51.473 --> 00:42:55.634
personally awards the SVT-40.
semi-automatic rifle

514
00:42:55.794 --> 00:42:57.914
to Red Army Woman Pavlichenko.

515
00:42:58.715 --> 00:43:01.913
A separate role is played by the air force

516
00:43:01.955 --> 00:43:04.074
in the destruction of enemy forces-

517
00:43:04.876 --> 00:43:06.635
Company. attention!

518
00:43:09.917 --> 00:43:13.436
Soldier Pavlichenko. L.M.. step forward!

519
00:43:13.478 --> 00:43:14.516
Sir!

520
00:43:16.558 --> 00:43:18.597
Huh! Really?

521
00:43:21.319 --> 00:43:24.758
L.M. Pavlichenko. are you the daughter
of the Mikhail Pavlichenko

522
00:43:24.800 --> 00:43:26.718
who fought in the civil war?

523
00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:27.760
Yes Sir.

524
00:43:28.320 --> 00:43:30.280
Brave man. Mikhail.

525
00:43:30.720 --> 00:43:35.561
Ah. well then. if you need anything.
let me know.

526
00:43:35.761 --> 00:43:37.761
Congratulations. soldier Pavlichenko.

527
00:43:38.002 --> 00:43:39.721
Thank you. Comrade General.

528
00:43:39.883 --> 00:43:41.682
See comrades.

529
00:43:42.803 --> 00:43:46.043
This is my friend from the civil
war's daughter.

530
00:43:47.764 --> 00:43:50.643
Comrades. you should all follow
her fine example.

531
00:43:52.525 --> 00:43:54.685
Come on. say something
to your fellow soldiers.

532
00:43:58.086 --> 00:44:03.366
When I fight the enemy. I promise not to
hold back.

533
00:44:04.487 --> 00:44:07.326
and that I'll kill 100 fascists with
this rifle.

534
00:44:08.048 --> 00:44:10.046
- Dismissed. Commissar.
- Dismissed!

535
00:44:10.088 --> 00:44:11.207
Makarov.

536
00:44:13.449 --> 00:44:17.168
You keep an eye on her. If she
takes after her father. then...

537
00:44:17.649 --> 00:44:20.129
- Understood?
- Yes Sir. understood.

538
00:44:21.290 --> 00:44:24.930
A new rifle always needs adjusting
to fit you.

539
00:44:25.091 --> 00:44:26.969
No two rifles are the same.

540
00:44:27.011 --> 00:44:28.891
They each have their own character.

541
00:44:29.051 --> 00:44:32.410
You need to understand the rifle. and treat
it carefully too.

542
00:44:32.452 --> 00:44:35.172
just like you would a wife.

543
00:44:39.493 --> 00:44:41.494
Are you married Comrade Captain?

544
00:44:44.294 --> 00:44:46.254
No. I'm not.

545
00:44:50.295 --> 00:44:56.016
I was once.
At first I was afraid of getting married.

546
00:44:57.337 --> 00:45:00.777
When I got back from the Winter War.
I couldn't believe.

547
00:45:01.178 --> 00:45:04.538
that such a young and
beautiful woman loved me.

548
00:45:06.499 --> 00:45:08.178
But when this war started...

549
00:45:11.820 --> 00:45:13.900
I was too late. I couldn't save her.

550
00:45:16.100 --> 00:45:17.420
<i>- Lyuda!</i>
- Maria.

551
00:45:18.421 --> 00:45:19.421
Maria!

552
00:45:19.741 --> 00:45:20.979
Lyuda!

553
00:45:21.021 --> 00:45:22.901
Ma... Maria!

554
00:45:23.062 --> 00:45:24.301
Finally. I found you.

555
00:45:24.343 --> 00:45:25.703
- What are you doing here?
- Lyuda.

556
00:45:25.745 --> 00:45:26.904
How did you... Why...

557
00:45:27.382 --> 00:45:31.421
Oh Lyuda. There's so many things that
I need to tell you.

558
00:45:31.463 --> 00:45:33.983
We get to fight together now.
me. you and Gregory.

559
00:45:34.864 --> 00:45:36.383
Gregory? Who's Gregory?

560
00:45:36.905 --> 00:45:38.943
Huh? Did you forget?

561
00:45:38.985 --> 00:45:40.943
My pilot. Gregory.

562
00:45:40.985 --> 00:45:42.024
My Greg.

563
00:45:44.786 --> 00:45:46.306
Is he yours?

564
00:45:55.988 --> 00:45:57.108
He will be.

565
00:46:06.711 --> 00:46:08.510
<b>The White House. USA. 1942</b>

566
00:46:34.595 --> 00:46:35.595
I'm Russian.

567
00:46:36.228 --> 00:46:39.714
And somehow managed to get out of
Russia in '28.

568
00:46:39.756 --> 00:46:41.436
I have every right.

569
00:47:47.209 --> 00:47:50.769
Comrade Captain.
<b>Odessa. September 1941</b>

570
00:47:50.930 --> 00:47:52.450
got three more to add to the count.

571
00:47:52.610 --> 00:47:55.450
You can record them. we've
verified the kills.

572
00:47:55.611 --> 00:47:59.250
She took out two instantly. but then waited
for the third.

573
00:47:59.292 --> 00:48:00.491
We even had a bet going.

574
00:48:00.852 --> 00:48:04.093
The German lit up a cigarette. thinking we
couldn't see him. She proved him wrong.

575
00:48:04.252 --> 00:48:07.252
We had to crawl up. Here.

576
00:48:09.893 --> 00:48:13.373
Well. they do say that smoking is
bad for your health.

577
00:48:14.254 --> 00:48:17.454
Lyuda. are you coming
on recon this evening?

578
00:48:17.615 --> 00:48:19.654
We'll keep you safe and warm.

579
00:48:19.696 --> 00:48:20.855
It's warm here already.

580
00:48:21.415 --> 00:48:23.413
Well. we'll wait for you in any case.

581
00:48:26.216 --> 00:48:29.897
<b>Directive: The undersigned confirms that
Red Army Woman Pavlichenko...</b>

582
00:48:30.378 --> 00:48:35.418
Hmm. Lyuda. perhaps a medal might be in
the offing for you.

583
00:48:37.299 --> 00:48:41.659
Comrade Captain. did you have any hits
at nighttime?

584
00:48:43.580 --> 00:48:45.419
Yeah. All sorts.

585
00:48:47.781 --> 00:48:52.061
I remember in Finland. I went out hunting.

586
00:48:53.062 --> 00:48:56.422
Then I see an interesting position open up.

587
00:48:58.862 --> 00:49:01.742
I see that if I take aim
from this one spot.

588
00:49:03.504 --> 00:49:06.423
then I could take down three targets with
a single bullet.

589
00:49:07.904 --> 00:49:12.625
So I lie there and wait. Bang!
And I made the shot.

590
00:49:15.226 --> 00:49:16.609
Yet they only counted one.

591
00:49:19.451 --> 00:49:21.026
They didn't believe me.

592
00:49:21.187 --> 00:49:22.947
that I did that with one shot.

593
00:49:25.507 --> 00:49:26.547
Three huh?

594
00:49:45.712 --> 00:49:47.110
<i>We need a connection. now.</i>

595
00:49:47.152 --> 00:49:49.712
<i>I'm trying Comrade Sergeant. I'm trying.</i>

596
00:49:53.513 --> 00:49:54.592
- Philipchuk.
- Yes Sir?

597
00:49:55.474 --> 00:49:56.911
Where's Pavlichenko?

598
00:49:56.953 --> 00:49:59.066
She went out to the
right. changed position.

599
00:50:12.940 --> 00:50:14.036
It's okay.

600
00:50:19.278 --> 00:50:20.661
Come on.

601
00:50:30.480 --> 00:50:31.759
[German] Water.

602
00:51:15.328 --> 00:51:17.296
Pavlichenko. to me!

603
00:51:19.370 --> 00:51:23.129
Pavlichenko. who authorised you to
leave your position?

604
00:51:23.290 --> 00:51:24.851
Can't we talk about this in the trench?

605
00:51:25.410 --> 00:51:26.969
Be brave!

606
00:51:29.932 --> 00:51:31.131
Hold on!

607
00:51:36.692 --> 00:51:37.972
What's the time.

608
00:51:41.493 --> 00:51:42.493
There.

609
00:51:45.655 --> 00:51:48.813
- Come on handsome.
- Okay. go.

610
00:51:48.855 --> 00:51:51.934
Come on. that's enough.

611
00:51:59.817 --> 00:52:01.296
Get up. come on!

612
00:52:10.059 --> 00:52:11.459
<i>Still no connection.</i>

613
00:52:11.619 --> 00:52:13.137
What have you done. you idiot?

614
00:52:13.179 --> 00:52:16.379
You showed me yourself how to take them
out faster.

615
00:52:16.540 --> 00:52:18.060
I wouldn't be on my 73rd without you.

616
00:52:18.940 --> 00:52:20.619
They could have killed you.

617
00:52:20.661 --> 00:52:21.740
You as well.

618
00:52:21.981 --> 00:52:22.981
Stop.

619
00:52:24.542 --> 00:52:27.461
Do you want to end up in front
of a tribunal for your antics?

620
00:52:30.543 --> 00:52:31.981
Back to your position.

621
00:52:32.023 --> 00:52:33.142
Yes Sir.

622
00:52:39.824 --> 00:52:42.944
Comrade Captain. to the right of the
forest. next to the crater.

623
00:52:47.986 --> 00:52:50.745
Do woundeds count?
That's another one to write down.

624
00:52:50.787 --> 00:52:53.626
Stop it you idiot! Stop it!

625
00:52:53.987 --> 00:52:55.186
You're hurting me.

626
00:53:05.110 --> 00:53:07.029
I dragged two of them out today.

627
00:53:10.070 --> 00:53:12.349
That's makes it 20 for me now.

628
00:53:14.311 --> 00:53:17.951
Wait. actually it's 21. Blow.

629
00:53:18.471 --> 00:53:19.951
Yeah. 21.

630
00:53:20.272 --> 00:53:21.792
I've taken out 73 krauts.

631
00:53:22.192 --> 00:53:25.633
Could've been more if it weren't
for Makarov.

632
00:53:26.193 --> 00:53:27.872
Permission to come aboard?

633
00:53:27.914 --> 00:53:29.273
Granted!

634
00:53:30.114 --> 00:53:31.514
Hello Lyuda.

635
00:53:31.954 --> 00:53:33.994
<i>I've missed you so much!</i>

636
00:53:46.277 --> 00:53:47.756
Good evening Captain.

637
00:53:49.158 --> 00:53:50.793
Why are you doing that yourself?
We have

638
00:53:50.835 --> 00:53:52.758
dozens of girls who can
sew for you. ask them.

639
00:53:54.319 --> 00:53:57.319
I like it. it's relaxing.

640
00:54:06.048 --> 00:54:08.690
The order's been received
to start preparations

641
00:54:08.732 --> 00:54:10.800
for evacuating the
troops to Crimea.

642
00:54:11.962 --> 00:54:14.321
The troops will pull out to the port.

643
00:54:14.363 --> 00:54:16.842
your objective is to cover the withdrawal.

644
00:54:19.203 --> 00:54:23.539
Here... and here.

645
00:54:25.244 --> 00:54:26.804
We leave tomorrow.

646
00:54:33.686 --> 00:54:36.806
So what. we just give up Odessa?
We could still hold it.

647
00:54:38.127 --> 00:54:39.224
Well. command knows best.

648
00:54:41.392 --> 00:54:43.007
I'm from Odessa.

649
00:54:43.928 --> 00:54:47.248
Thinking about how there will be fascists
all around the Duke de Richelieu Monument.

650
00:54:47.809 --> 00:54:49.528
it makes me sick to my stomach.

651
00:54:50.929 --> 00:54:53.328
So I'm supposed to just cut through
straight there?

652
00:54:53.370 --> 00:54:55.169
Yes. just make sure you keep to the left.

653
00:54:56.330 --> 00:54:57.489
All the best.

654
00:55:06.052 --> 00:55:08.092
<i>Come on. open up. got no brakes.</i>

655
00:55:08.357 --> 00:55:10.204
<i>- Okay. one sec.
- Thanks.</i>

656
00:55:12.013 --> 00:55:17.693
<i>♪ Those who haven't known love.</i>

657
00:55:17.735 --> 00:55:22.734
<i>♪ will also never know sorrow.</i>

658
00:55:23.496 --> 00:55:29.095
<i>♪ And I am but a young maiden.</i>

659
00:55:29.137 --> 00:55:34.537
♪ I will not sleep.

660
00:55:35.618 --> 00:55:41.697
♪ I will find him.

661
00:55:41.739 --> 00:55:46.699
♪ Day and night waiting.

662
00:55:46.900 --> 00:55:48.779
Let's drink.

663
00:55:48.821 --> 00:55:52.619
- Let's drink to Odessa.
- ♪ I will...

664
00:55:52.661 --> 00:55:57.461
- To the city which we...
- To the city where I fell in love.

665
00:55:57.942 --> 00:55:58.942
Yes.

666
00:56:00.062 --> 00:56:01.302
<i>To Odessa!</i>

667
00:56:06.183 --> 00:56:08.343
Oh. by the way. we're out of fuel.

668
00:56:09.464 --> 00:56:11.704
I've still got some left.
Back in a second.

669
00:56:13.665 --> 00:56:15.105
Excuse me.

670
00:56:17.346 --> 00:56:20.025
<i>Maria. stop! That's an order.</i>

671
00:56:25.147 --> 00:56:26.267
Gregory...

672
00:56:42.910 --> 00:56:46.270
I was looking forward to getting some
time alone together.

673
00:56:48.151 --> 00:56:49.671
Why?

674
00:56:54.113 --> 00:56:56.032
That's enough! Stop it!

675
00:56:59.634 --> 00:57:01.633
I don't love you.

676
00:57:01.914 --> 00:57:05.337
<i>We're all adults here.
War and death are everywhere we look.</i>

677
00:57:05.499 --> 00:57:06.914
<i>They could kill us both tomorrow.</i>

678
00:57:11.036 --> 00:57:14.514
<i>You're hurting me! Stop it!
You're hurting me!</i>

679
00:57:14.556 --> 00:57:16.036
<i>You fucking bitch!</i>

680
00:57:23.318 --> 00:57:26.437
Thank you. But I don't need saving
that often.

681
00:57:26.479 --> 00:57:29.879
Hey. you should have said that you had
a boyfriend. But you...

682
00:57:30.039 --> 00:57:31.439
Don't interrupt!

683
00:57:57.805 --> 00:57:58.964
I'm sorry.

684
00:58:00.565 --> 00:58:01.644
For what?

685
00:58:03.645 --> 00:58:05.325
I made a promise.

686
00:58:06.847 --> 00:58:07.886
To who?

687
00:58:11.207 --> 00:58:12.487
Myself.

688
00:58:20.729 --> 00:58:22.288
Let me help you.

689
00:58:29.810 --> 00:58:31.650
Okay. go on then. help me.

690
00:58:34.731 --> 00:58:36.291
Not like that.

691
00:58:38.612 --> 00:58:40.052
Because of someone else?

692
00:58:40.573 --> 00:58:43.573
Because of the war. If they hurt you...

693
00:58:43.733 --> 00:58:45.053
You're a coward. Comrade Captain.

694
00:58:49.494 --> 00:58:51.413
You need to have faith
that they won't kill us.

695
00:59:41.384 --> 00:59:45.584
Lyuda! Can you hear me? Lyuda. breathe!

696
00:59:48.065 --> 00:59:49.585
Come on. a little further!

697
00:59:50.666 --> 00:59:53.585
Giddyup! Faster!

698
00:59:56.107 --> 00:59:57.426
Come on! Breathe!

699
01:00:07.549 --> 01:00:08.948
Can you hear me?

700
01:00:27.192 --> 01:00:29.152
Shh! It's okay. I'm here.

701
01:00:30.713 --> 01:00:33.913
Makarov? Makarov.

702
01:00:37.355 --> 01:00:39.233
- I love you.
- Shh.

703
01:00:39.275 --> 01:00:41.195
- I love you.
- Shh. quiet. shh.

704
01:00:42.675 --> 01:00:44.515
Easy. shh.

705
01:00:48.877 --> 01:00:53.797
Sleep. and everything will be okay.

706
01:01:00.919 --> 01:01:04.959
Dr Chopak. Mr Polyakov is running a fever.
he's delirious again.

707
01:01:07.320 --> 01:01:09.800
Well. change his bandages then.

708
01:01:10.921 --> 01:01:13.001
Dr Chopak. change what bandages?

709
01:01:13.602 --> 01:01:16.921
Um... I... yes. sorry.

710
01:01:30.485 --> 01:01:33.285
Comrade Doctor! Comrade Doctor!

711
01:01:35.806 --> 01:01:37.844
I have a personal favour to ask you.

712
01:01:37.886 --> 01:01:40.846
Miss Pavlichenko. she's very dear and
important to me.

713
01:01:41.527 --> 01:01:43.206
Please look after her for me.

714
01:01:43.848 --> 01:01:45.806
We look after everybody well here.

715
01:01:45.968 --> 01:01:49.488
But she's not everyone. She's special.
She's...

716
01:01:49.648 --> 01:01:51.408
I know that she's special.

717
01:01:54.129 --> 01:01:57.649
I love her too and have
done for a long while.

718
01:02:02.091 --> 01:02:04.130
Well then. that's good.

719
01:02:05.644 --> 01:02:08.931
You'll look after her.

720
01:02:09.692 --> 01:02:13.812
and then she can decide herself who she
wants to stay with.

721
01:02:14.493 --> 01:02:16.933
It's a pity that you couldn't look after
her as well.

722
01:02:27.215 --> 01:02:29.295
<b>The White House. USA. 1942.</b>

723
01:04:05.394 --> 01:04:10.226
<b>Evacuation to Sevastopol. Autumn 1941.</b>

724
01:04:25.678 --> 01:04:29.277
Here. take this!

725
01:04:29.902 --> 01:04:30.902
Eat!

726
01:04:44.002 --> 01:04:46.440
Lyuda. I wanted to ask you...

727
01:05:27.650 --> 01:05:28.650
Lyuda.

728
01:06:10.697 --> 01:06:13.073
Sweetie. don't be scared.
Don't be scared my dear.

729
01:06:13.234 --> 01:06:16.698
Don't shiver like that.
it's all gonna be fine.

730
01:06:24.980 --> 01:06:29.261
Gregory's flying over us. Look. over there.
He's flying.

731
01:06:29.421 --> 01:06:32.821
Don't be scared. everything will be fine.
Have faith. You'll see Makarov soon. Drink!

732
01:07:07.948 --> 01:07:09.828
- Don't be scared.
- Are you okay? Are you okay?

733
01:07:09.870 --> 01:07:11.276
<i>Someone help! Got wounded here.</i>

734
01:07:11.389 --> 01:07:13.588
- I'll be right back.
- No!

735
01:07:13.630 --> 01:07:15.909
- Don't move.
- I have to get up. I need to.

736
01:07:16.070 --> 01:07:17.231
You're not a soldier anymore.

737
01:07:18.791 --> 01:07:21.430
Come on. You're injured now.

738
01:07:21.591 --> 01:07:23.151
You can't go to the frontline anymore.

739
01:07:23.872 --> 01:07:25.311
You don't understand! I have to.

740
01:07:25.992 --> 01:07:28.672
I can't make you better
while we're out here.

741
01:07:30.433 --> 01:07:33.912
Then just make me well enough.
Come on.

742
01:07:34.074 --> 01:07:37.753
They've discharged you.
I'm a doctor. not a magician.

743
01:07:42.315 --> 01:07:43.353
At ease.

744
01:07:43.395 --> 01:07:47.003
<b>Regional Defence HQ.
Sevastopol. November 1941.</b>

745
01:07:47.356 --> 01:07:48.915
General Zaporozhets!

746
01:07:51.557 --> 01:07:52.875
Oh. hello Lyudmila.

747
01:07:52.917 --> 01:07:54.996
Can you sign my fit-to-return papers?

748
01:07:56.238 --> 01:07:58.237
Congratulations on your recovery.

749
01:08:01.759 --> 01:08:05.759
Tell you what. come with me.
I'll treat you to some tea.

750
01:08:06.999 --> 01:08:09.600
What's wrong with your arm?
She's with me.

751
01:08:10.720 --> 01:08:12.360
<i>Hey. watch out!</i>

752
01:08:16.082 --> 01:08:18.009
<i>Attention on the floor!</i>

753
01:08:20.162 --> 01:08:21.602
Wait here please.

754
01:08:22.883 --> 01:08:26.041
<i>The order received from headquarters
is to not surrender the city.</i>

755
01:08:26.083 --> 01:08:28.002
Hold it at all costs.

756
01:08:29.364 --> 01:08:33.964
Ah. here's General Petrov. He's just now
arrived back from the front-lines.

757
01:08:34.605 --> 01:08:37.511
I'm sure he'll have lots of observations
to tell us about.

758
01:08:37.553 --> 01:08:38.869
<i>Go ahead General.</i>

759
01:08:40.606 --> 01:08:45.846
The outer defensive line now runs 13
kilometres from Sevastopol.

760
01:08:46.007 --> 01:08:48.766
Thus. the city has now become vulnerable to
German artillery fire.

761
01:08:49.367 --> 01:08:53.446
Despite our efforts. we cannot drive the
enemy any farther back from the city.

762
01:08:53.488 --> 01:08:56.528
But even if we could. the defensive line
would be stretched

763
01:08:56.647 --> 01:08:58.087
and we'd be unable to hold position.

764
01:08:58.129 --> 01:08:59.568
So how can we defend the city?

765
01:09:00.370 --> 01:09:05.010
One shrapnel shell from our battleship gun
would be able

766
01:09:05.171 --> 01:09:09.289
to strike an area 250 metres wide and one
kilometre deep.

767
01:09:09.331 --> 01:09:12.531
Just on the Paris Commune battleship alone.

768
01:09:12.692 --> 01:09:14.611
we have 12 such guns.

769
01:09:14.653 --> 01:09:18.212
Their fire could suppress
the artillery of the enemy.

770
01:09:18.614 --> 01:09:21.373
But as I've just learned.
according to your orders.

771
01:09:21.533 --> 01:09:24.492
almost all of the ships are being deployed
to the Caucasus.

772
01:09:24.534 --> 01:09:28.333
I recommend immediately bringing the
ships back as a matter of necessity.

773
01:09:28.375 --> 01:09:31.175
My objective is the defence
of the naval fleet.

774
01:09:31.294 --> 01:09:33.255
And in these present
circumstances. I cannot have-

775
01:09:33.297 --> 01:09:35.654
Our mission is to defend Sevastopol!

776
01:09:35.696 --> 01:09:38.176
The battleground has long
since shifted to land.

777
01:09:38.337 --> 01:09:41.976
but your unwillingness or inability
to learn about war in the field

778
01:09:42.018 --> 01:09:45.177
has led us to massive casualties amongst
the naval units.

779
01:09:45.338 --> 01:09:47.159
You don't use trenches.
don't use camouflage.

780
01:09:47.201 --> 01:09:48.497
or even keep low while fighting.

781
01:09:48.539 --> 01:09:51.537
Why isn't even changing the
uniform being considered?

782
01:09:51.579 --> 01:09:53.579
Our uniform is our pride!

783
01:10:00.461 --> 01:10:06.060
Gentlemen. I'd like you to meet Comrade
Sergeant Lyudmila Pavlichenko.

784
01:10:06.102 --> 01:10:08.742
Our very own heaven-sent sniper.

785
01:10:08.903 --> 01:10:10.782
Now. tell us please.

786
01:10:11.463 --> 01:10:14.703
in a real-life battle situation. who has
the greater chance of survival?

787
01:10:14.904 --> 01:10:19.783
Me. in a protective shirt. or this
gentleman. wearing a thick black jacket?

788
01:10:19.825 --> 01:10:22.504
Anyone in jackets. I kill first.

789
01:10:22.706 --> 01:10:25.226
But you. Comrade General. would take
a little searching to find.

790
01:10:26.106 --> 01:10:27.266
There we are.

791
01:10:27.666 --> 01:10:29.026
Thank you Lyudmila.

792
01:10:30.227 --> 01:10:33.987
Dyachenko! Prepare an order regarding
uniform substitution in the field.

793
01:10:34.147 --> 01:10:37.747
General Zaporozhets. what about my report?

794
01:10:38.508 --> 01:10:41.482
Well. if the doctors
have given you the

795
01:10:41.524 --> 01:10:45.068
all-clear. then fight to
your heart's content.

796
01:10:50.150 --> 01:10:51.470
<i>Are there any serious?</i>

797
01:10:53.007 --> 01:10:54.079
Be careful!

798
01:11:03.377 --> 01:11:04.641
<i>Where to then?</i>

799
01:11:10.994 --> 01:11:13.353
Come on! Move. move.

800
01:11:13.395 --> 01:11:14.674
Out of the way.

801
01:11:15.235 --> 01:11:17.195
Get out the road. quick!

802
01:11:17.715 --> 01:11:19.554
How many free beds are
left in the hospital?

803
01:11:19.596 --> 01:11:22.436
Boris. I need you to sign my
certificate saying I'm fit to return.

804
01:11:25.157 --> 01:11:27.204
Dr Chopak. Sidorenko's lost large amounts
of blood.

805
01:11:27.246 --> 01:11:29.816
He's going to require amputation
of his left and right limbs.

806
01:11:29.858 --> 01:11:32.797
Okay. take him to the third floor
immediately and prepare him for surgery.

807
01:11:32.841 --> 01:11:33.980
Right.

808
01:11:34.023 --> 01:11:37.440
Zhuk's been diagnosed with a
severe infection of the liver.

809
01:11:37.559 --> 01:11:38.559
Zhuk?

810
01:11:41.400 --> 01:11:43.120
Send him into the main hospital.

811
01:11:43.280 --> 01:11:45.160
Vadim! Vadim!

812
01:11:50.362 --> 01:11:54.362
Where are they? Where are our people?
Where's Makarov?

813
01:11:55.123 --> 01:11:56.441
- Look!
- There they go.

814
01:11:56.483 --> 01:11:57.923
There they are. can we go meet them?

815
01:12:06.405 --> 01:12:09.684
<i>Faster. faster. faster!
Look at that gun!</i>

816
01:12:27.889 --> 01:12:29.008
Lyuda!

817
01:12:31.570 --> 01:12:33.329
It's good that you're here.

818
01:12:38.811 --> 01:12:41.811
I promised Makarov.

819
01:12:42.132 --> 01:12:44.651
He wanted you to have this.

820
01:12:56.486 --> 01:12:59.494
<i>What can you do. it's war.</i>

821
01:13:01.664 --> 01:13:03.367
You have to live...

822
01:13:04.296 --> 01:13:05.655
You have to.

823
01:13:19.058 --> 01:13:20.096
Boris!

824
01:13:20.138 --> 01:13:23.418
- Lyuda. where did you disappear to?
- I have to be at the front. sign this!

825
01:13:23.628 --> 01:13:25.979
Please don't be offended. but...

826
01:13:27.754 --> 01:13:29.636
You've still got post-concussion syndrome.

827
01:13:29.679 --> 01:13:30.697
<i>You're free to go.</i>

828
01:13:30.740 --> 01:13:33.779
It would be murder to send you to
the front. I can't allow it myself.

829
01:13:33.821 --> 01:13:35.260
Makarov is dead.

830
01:13:40.223 --> 01:13:41.382
Are you listening?

831
01:13:42.703 --> 01:13:43.863
I'm sorry.

832
01:13:48.064 --> 01:13:51.103
Wait. Boris. You don't understand.
This is something that I...

833
01:13:52.305 --> 01:13:54.824
<b>Fit for duty.</b> <b>B. Chopak.</b>

834
01:14:07.628 --> 01:14:09.867
Thank you Boris.

835
01:14:22.207 --> 01:14:24.057
<b>The White House. USA. 1942.</b>

836
01:14:24.099 --> 01:14:25.099
Yes?

837
01:16:13.276 --> 01:16:16.652
I'm your new commander.
let's go kill some fascists!

838
01:16:16.812 --> 01:16:19.530
<b>Sevastopol. November 1941</b>
Oi. Maria. you idiot.

839
01:16:19.572 --> 01:16:21.371
<b>Sevastopol. November 1941</b>
Lyuda. Lyuda. look!

840
01:16:21.413 --> 01:16:23.332
Lyuda. Lyuda. look!

841
01:16:24.414 --> 01:16:26.341
What have I got here?

842
01:16:28.254 --> 01:16:30.181
I traded them for alcohol.

843
01:16:31.775 --> 01:16:32.894
And...

844
01:16:36.456 --> 01:16:39.375
Ta-da! Ta-da!

845
01:16:40.137 --> 01:16:45.217
So. this. this one's smaller. that's mine.
And this larger one's for you.

846
01:16:46.298 --> 01:16:47.456
Thanks.

847
01:16:47.498 --> 01:16:49.816
'Thanks'. That's all I get?

848
01:16:49.858 --> 01:16:52.298
Thanks. The frost's coming in now.

849
01:16:52.458 --> 01:16:55.378
So here's me. crawling around on these
rocks. and you're just lying there.

850
01:16:55.420 --> 01:16:57.341
You still want to be able
to have kids don't you.

851
01:16:57.383 --> 01:17:00.020
I think we... next time.
we should go together.

852
01:17:00.404 --> 01:17:02.405
We'll go together to
Gregory's. visit him together.

853
01:17:02.581 --> 01:17:06.101
He must be really lonely there now.

854
01:17:06.422 --> 01:17:08.597
y'know. after they grounded Nikolai.

855
01:17:15.431 --> 01:17:16.431
I'm sorry.

856
01:17:16.664 --> 01:17:17.703
It's alright.

857
01:17:21.504 --> 01:17:24.704
Have you seen your new commander?
Cute. right?

858
01:17:24.865 --> 01:17:26.944
- No.
- No he's not cute?

859
01:17:28.554 --> 01:17:29.569
No I haven't seen him.

860
01:17:30.786 --> 01:17:35.146
Ha. I bet that you're imagining he's
a geriatric or something.

861
01:17:36.067 --> 01:17:39.227
But he's really young. so...
Ah. damn.

862
01:17:39.483 --> 01:17:42.900
Since he's so young. we need to start
chasing after him immediately.

863
01:17:49.310 --> 01:17:52.509
Captain Leonid Kitsenko.
your new commander.

864
01:17:52.942 --> 01:17:54.790
May I join you?

865
01:17:55.151 --> 01:17:57.270
We're going to be carrying out a
special assignment:

866
01:17:58.031 --> 01:18:00.830
Sabotaging the home-front and hunting
for enemy snipers.

867
01:18:00.872 --> 01:18:02.749
And we're leaving on
this mission tomorrow?

868
01:18:02.791 --> 01:18:03.846
Yes.

869
01:18:03.889 --> 01:18:07.372
Then will you authorise the collection
of the ID tags from the bodies so...

870
01:18:07.415 --> 01:18:08.834
Lyudmila! You need to eat.

871
01:18:59.923 --> 01:19:01.402
As you were.

872
01:19:06.564 --> 01:19:08.203
We're leaving.

873
01:19:12.006 --> 01:19:13.525
Follow me.

874
01:19:17.246 --> 01:19:20.766
Stop. Stop! About face!

875
01:19:24.047 --> 01:19:26.927
You can't do that. We are not fascists
like them.

876
01:19:27.321 --> 01:19:29.247
Why didn't you let me kill him?

877
01:19:29.289 --> 01:19:31.767
They don't deserve a quick death.
They killed-

878
01:19:31.809 --> 01:19:37.529
This isn't about them. it's about you. You
can't live just for the sake of revenge.

879
01:19:38.891 --> 01:19:43.211
This war isn't only about death.
it's about life too.

880
01:19:43.971 --> 01:19:46.039
If your mind isn't
focussed on that. and you

881
01:19:46.081 --> 01:19:48.010
live for the war. then
you won't survive.

882
01:19:48.052 --> 01:19:49.731
Let them kill me. what d'you care?

883
01:19:50.173 --> 01:19:53.252
I don't want to lose any more friends.

884
01:20:07.534 --> 01:20:10.494
- <i>♪ How many songs are left to write?</i>
- You two. here are your two targets.

885
01:20:10.536 --> 01:20:13.696
- <i>♪ How many songs are left to write?</i>
- This machinery is a high profile target.

886
01:20:13.738 --> 01:20:17.211
- <i>♪ Tell me cuckoo. sing it aloud.</i>
- It's a long shot.

887
01:20:20.258 --> 01:20:23.698
- <i>♪ To live in the city or the village.</i>
- Listen to your heart.

888
01:20:24.019 --> 01:20:26.149
<i>♪ To lie like a stone.
or burn like a star?</i>

889
01:20:26.191 --> 01:20:27.418
Fire between the beats.

890
01:20:29.492 --> 01:20:30.971
<i>♪ Like a star.</i>

891
01:20:32.661 --> 01:20:37.020
<i>♪ Sunlight of mine. look at me now.</i> - The
area you're operating in is dangerous...

892
01:20:39.566 --> 01:20:43.302
<i>♪ My palm has turned into a fist.</i>

893
01:20:45.063 --> 01:20:46.225
I'm taking it.

894
01:20:46.267 --> 01:20:50.063
<i>♪ And if there's gunpowder.
give me the match.</i>

895
01:21:09.067 --> 01:21:11.763
<i>♪ Where are you now. my free-will?</i>

896
01:21:11.948 --> 01:21:16.180
<i>♪ Who are you with. greeting the sunrise?</i>

897
01:21:17.901 --> 01:21:20.981
<i>♪ Answer me!</i>

898
01:21:21.741 --> 01:21:24.630
<i>♪ There's good times with
you. but bad without.</i>

899
01:21:25.006 --> 01:21:29.239
<i>♪ My head and my shoulders are giving out.</i>

900
01:21:30.599 --> 01:21:31.911
- <i>♪ Giving out.</i>
- Take it.

901
01:21:35.568 --> 01:21:39.609
<i>♪ You are my sun. look at me please.</i>

902
01:21:42.001 --> 01:21:45.370
<i>♪ My palm has turned into a fist.</i>

903
01:21:48.242 --> 01:21:53.531
<i>♪ And if there's gunpowder.
give me the match.</i>

904
01:21:57.172 --> 01:21:59.100
<i>♪ That's how.</i>

905
01:22:13.360 --> 01:22:16.319
It's from 1919.

906
01:22:17.760 --> 01:22:19.399
To Greg. for his medal!

907
01:22:20.521 --> 01:22:24.401
So there's me. there's him. and I sneak up
from behind and bam!

908
01:22:24.561 --> 01:22:25.801
And that's it. he's out.

909
01:22:32.883 --> 01:22:34.323
[German] <i>Merry Christmas!</i>

910
01:22:41.117 --> 01:22:42.604
They're celebrating.

911
01:22:45.846 --> 01:22:47.949
[German] <i>To the Fuhrer!</i>

912
01:22:49.886 --> 01:22:52.006
It's Christmas for them.

913
01:23:16.492 --> 01:23:21.251
If you don't want want to surrender
everything to a fascist with a gun forever:

914
01:23:21.452 --> 01:23:24.292
Your house. your wife. your mother.

915
01:23:24.453 --> 01:23:26.972
everything that we call our motherland.

916
01:23:27.133 --> 01:23:31.213
Then know this: No one will save it.

917
01:23:31.255 --> 01:23:32.733
if you don't save it.

918
01:23:32.775 --> 01:23:35.813
Know this: No one will kill him.

919
01:23:35.855 --> 01:23:38.295
if you do not kill him.

920
01:23:38.456 --> 01:23:42.534
So kill the fascist. so that it is him.
and not you.

921
01:23:42.576 --> 01:23:44.216
who's lying in the ground.

922
01:23:44.376 --> 01:23:47.416
so that it's not your house where
grief is walking.

923
01:23:47.578 --> 01:23:50.177
but his house where death stands.

924
01:23:50.818 --> 01:23:53.936
So kill that fascist!

925
01:23:53.978 --> 01:23:57.058
And kill him quickly!

926
01:23:57.739 --> 01:24:02.379
However many times you see one.

927
01:24:02.581 --> 01:24:04.940
that's how many times you should kill one.

928
01:24:10.982 --> 01:24:12.781
- Bravo!
- Hey. don't leave yet.

929
01:24:14.823 --> 01:24:16.622
- Bravo!
- Bravo!

930
01:24:18.583 --> 01:24:23.063
Hitler wanted to celebrate the New Year in
Sevastopol this very night.

931
01:24:24.984 --> 01:24:27.783
but thanks to our steadfastness. it is
us who are celebrating.

932
01:24:27.825 --> 01:24:31.784
Once again. we have repelled the enemy

933
01:24:31.986 --> 01:24:33.945
from the walls of the city.

934
01:24:34.586 --> 01:24:39.226
Sevastopol lives!
And Sevastopol will live!

935
01:24:40.667 --> 01:24:42.947
Leonid. I want you meet Boris.

936
01:24:45.468 --> 01:24:47.668
he's my friend from before the war.

937
01:24:48.429 --> 01:24:50.907
- Boris.
- Leonid.

938
01:24:50.949 --> 01:24:53.347
In view of the arrival of the ammunition.

939
01:24:53.389 --> 01:24:56.228
I'm ordering the immediate elimination

940
01:24:56.270 --> 01:24:59.909
of 1.500 boxes of champagne.

941
01:24:59.951 --> 01:25:02.342
We must all do our part to clear the
storage tunnels.

942
01:25:02.640 --> 01:25:07.143
Happy New Year 1942! Oo-rah comrades!

943
01:25:07.432 --> 01:25:08.912
<i>Oo-rah!</i>

944
01:25:12.953 --> 01:25:14.873
<i>For Comrade Stalin!</i>

945
01:25:20.058 --> 01:25:23.802
Stop! Don't open it yet.
I'll get some cups.

946
01:25:28.277 --> 01:25:31.436
The last time me and Lyudmila drank
champagne we were at my house.

947
01:25:37.118 --> 01:25:38.838
How long have you known each other?

948
01:25:38.998 --> 01:25:41.038
I fell in love with her before the war.

949
01:25:41.199 --> 01:25:43.657
On the whole. if it wasn't for her.
I doubt I'd be here.

950
01:25:43.760 --> 01:25:45.159
That's a shame.

951
01:25:45.680 --> 01:25:47.399
What is. that I fell in love with her?

952
01:25:47.920 --> 01:25:50.071
That you ended up in the war.

953
01:25:50.441 --> 01:25:55.200
No. because then I would have regretted
that I'd never fallen in love with her.

954
01:25:56.161 --> 01:25:58.401
At least here we sometimes see each other.

955
01:26:00.602 --> 01:26:04.403
And you? Do you love her too?

956
01:26:06.363 --> 01:26:07.763
<i>Take it easy! What're you doing?</i>

957
01:26:08.682 --> 01:26:09.682
<i>Watch your hands!</i>

958
01:26:09.724 --> 01:26:11.042
What's wrong little boy?

959
01:26:11.084 --> 01:26:12.485
Oh what. so it's only officers you-

960
01:26:15.213 --> 01:26:17.998
<i>- Officers' whore!
- Guys. guys!</i>

961
01:26:22.527 --> 01:26:24.968
<i>It's the Germans we need to be beating.
not each other's mugs.</i>

962
01:26:25.010 --> 01:26:26.010
Let go of me!

963
01:26:26.111 --> 01:26:27.150
<i>Stand down!</i>

964
01:26:37.290 --> 01:26:39.008
Happy New Year!

965
01:27:15.177 --> 01:27:17.896
I thought that this would happen
differently somehow.

966
01:28:11.027 --> 01:28:15.067
<b>Chicago. USA. 1942.</b>

967
01:29:07.276 --> 01:29:10.116
What is going on with you? Are you out
of your fucking mind Pavlichenko?

968
01:29:10.158 --> 01:29:11.679
You think I'm your damn agent do you?

969
01:30:29.853 --> 01:30:34.253
<b>Sevastopol. Spring 1942.</b>

970
01:30:54.586 --> 01:30:57.578
You know. I've decided that Gregory and
me are gonna have a boy.

971
01:30:58.138 --> 01:30:59.977
Are you out of your mind Maria?

972
01:31:00.019 --> 01:31:03.379
I really want one. my own child. right
in here.

973
01:31:05.020 --> 01:31:06.699
Greg's not against it.

974
01:31:22.543 --> 01:31:25.503
<i>Lyuda! I've got something to tell you.</i>

975
01:31:25.622 --> 01:31:26.622
What's happened Maria?

976
01:31:26.664 --> 01:31:28.063
Come on. I'll tell you.

977
01:31:28.105 --> 01:31:32.224
My very own mother and father would
like for me to invite the both of you

978
01:31:32.385 --> 01:31:34.705
to join us tomorrow for a
celebration of nuptials.

979
01:31:34.865 --> 01:31:36.345
- A what?
- A celebration of nuptials.

980
01:31:36.387 --> 01:31:39.907
A what? A wedding.
Nuptials. to celebrate. we invite you.

981
01:32:20.675 --> 01:32:23.194
- Uncle Leonid. Uncle Leonid!
- How many did you kill?

982
01:32:24.313 --> 01:32:25.313
Two.

983
01:32:25.355 --> 01:32:27.355
- Is that all.
- Not many.

984
01:32:28.707 --> 01:32:30.035
Auntie Lyuda. look!

985
01:32:31.556 --> 01:32:32.635
Oh. that's excellent.

986
01:32:32.677 --> 01:32:35.115
Did you see? I can already do it.

987
01:32:35.157 --> 01:32:38.036
Will you teach me how to shoot a rifle?

988
01:32:38.078 --> 01:32:39.196
And me. and me. and me!

989
01:32:39.358 --> 01:32:42.758
I will. I will. But not now. Keep
practising for the time being.

990
01:32:42.918 --> 01:32:44.558
I'm Lyuda now!

991
01:32:44.719 --> 01:32:46.277
No. I am. I'm Lyuda.

992
01:32:46.319 --> 01:32:47.998
No. no. no you're not. I am.

993
01:32:48.640 --> 01:32:50.799
Shoo! Out of the way! Out of the way!

994
01:32:53.441 --> 01:32:54.640
<i>No. I'm Lyuda!</i>

995
01:32:57.762 --> 01:33:01.441
You're late. I'm sorry.

996
01:33:02.274 --> 01:33:05.042
I invited you to a wedding. but it's
ended up as a wake.

997
01:33:07.323 --> 01:33:09.363
They killed Gregory.

998
01:33:11.123 --> 01:33:12.204
So let's honour his memory.

999
01:33:22.366 --> 01:33:23.965
In his memory.

1000
01:33:28.807 --> 01:33:30.326
I'm not upset.

1001
01:33:31.728 --> 01:33:34.327
Honestly. It's war. people get killed.

1002
01:33:37.009 --> 01:33:42.169
But we decided that together.
it wasn't so terrifying.

1003
01:33:45.171 --> 01:33:46.529
It was better together.

1004
01:33:47.475 --> 01:33:48.475
Lyuda.

1005
01:33:53.011 --> 01:33:54.411
Now you need to love.

1006
01:33:55.652 --> 01:34:00.371
You need to celebrate.

1007
01:34:00.413 --> 01:34:03.013
Above all. you should...

1008
01:34:04.094 --> 01:34:08.574
No. I will not stop celebrating.

1009
01:34:13.456 --> 01:34:17.816
Leonid. I want a son.

1010
01:34:24.738 --> 01:34:30.378
You said yourself that war was about
life. didn't you?

1011
01:35:03.185 --> 01:35:04.224
Yes.

1012
01:35:10.507 --> 01:35:13.626
<b>Chicago. USA. 1942.</b>

1013
01:35:13.827 --> 01:35:17.427
Pavlichenko. what is this. a masquerade?

1014
01:35:22.589 --> 01:35:25.629
You need to carry yourself with dignity.
with discipline.

1015
01:35:26.710 --> 01:35:28.629
They need to see that I'm a woman.

1016
01:35:32.150 --> 01:35:37.631
You're not a woman. You're a Soviet
soldier. Try remembering that.

1017
01:35:39.272 --> 01:35:41.683
When you're out there.
you represent Stalin.

1018
01:35:41.725 --> 01:35:44.232
Remember. the common
enemy. the second front.

1019
01:35:44.713 --> 01:35:46.434
This isn't some kind of
amateur performance.

1020
01:35:46.977 --> 01:35:47.977
Understood?

1021
01:35:51.874 --> 01:35:52.913
Yes Sir.

1022
01:36:36.203 --> 01:36:37.922
I can't do this anymore.

1023
01:36:52.685 --> 01:36:56.525
<b>Sevastopol. Summer 1942.</b>

1024
01:36:56.686 --> 01:36:57.806
Lyuda.

1025
01:37:05.608 --> 01:37:06.688
Lyuda. I-

1026
01:38:26.583 --> 01:38:30.135
Help us! Help us!

1027
01:38:34.895 --> 01:38:36.086
Help!

1028
01:38:44.271 --> 01:38:47.338
Someone help!

1029
01:38:49.548 --> 01:38:50.947
Help!

1030
01:38:52.555 --> 01:38:53.594
Leonid!

1031
01:39:03.270 --> 01:39:04.270
Leonid!

1032
01:39:13.472 --> 01:39:14.671
Leonid?

1033
01:39:16.081 --> 01:39:18.833
- Leonid? Where's Leonid?
- Shh. Shh.

1034
01:39:19.713 --> 01:39:21.272
Leonid's gone.

1035
01:39:21.732 --> 01:39:22.732
How? How is he gone?

1036
01:39:22.774 --> 01:39:24.489
Calm down. Can you hear me?
That's enough.

1037
01:39:24.874 --> 01:39:27.713
This is all my fault.
The war's over for you now.

1038
01:39:27.755 --> 01:39:30.462
You've been discharged as unfit for
active duty in the war.

1039
01:39:31.036 --> 01:39:33.715
Who are you to say when
someone's discharged?

1040
01:39:34.356 --> 01:39:38.395
Pavlichenko may not be a soldier. but she's
a symbol now.

1041
01:39:38.437 --> 01:39:40.396
And symbols do not get discharged.

1042
01:39:40.438 --> 01:39:42.475
I must ask you to immediately leave
this hospital.

1043
01:39:42.517 --> 01:39:44.838
Do you want to find yourself in front
of a tribunal? Go on.

1044
01:39:45.239 --> 01:39:49.117
This is not a sanctuary for your
friends from before the war.

1045
01:39:49.159 --> 01:39:52.399
Didn't you see? The Germans are reporting
about her death.

1046
01:39:52.839 --> 01:39:54.952
I've got a third wave drawing in.

1047
01:39:55.080 --> 01:39:57.841
and now my soldiers are going into battle
with her name haunting them.

1048
01:39:57.883 --> 01:39:59.922
I will be complaining to General Petrov.

1049
01:40:01.041 --> 01:40:04.160
These are his orders:
'Get her back on her feet. '

1050
01:40:04.202 --> 01:40:06.321
'We need her on the front.'

1051
01:40:06.699 --> 01:40:08.460
<i>- Lift your arms up higher please.
- I can't.</i>

1052
01:40:08.898 --> 01:40:12.243
- Let me do that.
- <i>Hurry up then.</i>

1053
01:40:18.204 --> 01:40:20.804
She's not really looking that heroic.

1054
01:40:23.245 --> 01:40:24.725
Come on. smile.

1055
01:40:25.966 --> 01:40:29.366
Hold your head up. More cheerful.

1056
01:42:14.346 --> 01:42:16.866
- Comrade Commissar.
- Ah. Pavlichenko. come in.

1057
01:42:17.747 --> 01:42:20.147
Here. look at this.

1058
01:42:20.988 --> 01:42:24.707
One of the best German snipers.
Otto von Singer.

1059
01:42:24.749 --> 01:42:26.027
they've sent him for you.

1060
01:42:26.069 --> 01:42:29.789
They believe that you're alive.
The photo worked.

1061
01:42:31.110 --> 01:42:35.068
And according to our current intelligence.
his nest can be found in this location.

1062
01:42:35.110 --> 01:42:37.990
I can't do it Comrade Commissar.

1063
01:42:39.031 --> 01:42:40.709
Hey Lyuda. stop messing around.

1064
01:42:40.751 --> 01:42:43.032
Don't you understand how important it is
to win this duel?

1065
01:42:43.074 --> 01:42:44.754
He's the best sniper. and I'm not anymore.

1066
01:42:44.882 --> 01:42:49.392
There's the certificate from your Dr
Chopak. I'm not fit for active duty.

1067
01:42:51.111 --> 01:42:53.712
Do you realise how many of your comrades
this sniper has murdered?

1068
01:42:54.234 --> 01:42:55.433
I can't do it.

1069
01:42:55.595 --> 01:42:57.473
You have to do this for my sake.

1070
01:42:57.515 --> 01:42:58.953
- I can't.
- For your own sake.

1071
01:42:58.995 --> 01:43:01.715
- I can't.
- For Leonid Kitsenko.

1072
01:43:05.716 --> 01:43:07.916
Fine.

1073
01:43:09.845 --> 01:43:10.845
Fine.

1074
01:46:22.433 --> 01:46:24.671
<i>Comrade Sergeant. where
are the boxes going?</i>

1075
01:46:24.713 --> 01:46:27.432
<i>- Put them on the truck dammit!
- But the truck isn't here.</i>

1076
01:46:27.474 --> 01:46:29.794
I'm here to see the General-Major.

1077
01:46:33.275 --> 01:46:34.835
Comrade General-Major.

1078
01:46:37.156 --> 01:46:38.356
What do you want?

1079
01:46:40.357 --> 01:46:43.637
It's imperative that First Sergeant
Pavlichenko be evacuated immediately.

1080
01:46:44.238 --> 01:46:45.836
And what about everyone else?

1081
01:46:46.238 --> 01:46:48.918
We're preparing to ship off archives
and documents at the moment.

1082
01:46:49.718 --> 01:46:52.308
From personnel I only
have orders to evacuate

1083
01:46:52.350 --> 01:46:54.638
party workers and
valuable specialists.

1084
01:46:54.800 --> 01:46:55.959
Those are my orders.

1085
01:46:56.120 --> 01:47:00.200
Hundreds of Germans killed. Four wounds on
the battlefield. Post-concussion syndrome.

1086
01:47:01.361 --> 01:47:04.960
And she is a woman at the end of the day.
Is she not valuable?

1087
01:47:06.402 --> 01:47:07.961
Hasn't she earned it?

1088
01:47:08.602 --> 01:47:10.841
<b>Evacuation order.</b> <b>B. Chopak.</b>

1089
01:47:24.901 --> 01:47:26.564
<i>We're Soviet citizens.</i>

1090
01:47:31.326 --> 01:47:33.246
<i>- Hold on!
- Let me through!</i>

1091
01:47:34.247 --> 01:47:36.408
<i>Please. I lost my travel papers.
I'm a military doctor.</i>

1092
01:47:36.928 --> 01:47:38.927
I have evacuation papers.

1093
01:47:42.569 --> 01:47:44.287
<i>I'm a party worker!</i>

1094
01:47:51.090 --> 01:47:53.610
- Lyuda. hold on. I'll just be a sec.
- Where are you going?

1095
01:47:53.971 --> 01:47:54.971
<i>Let me through!</i>

1096
01:48:00.491 --> 01:48:03.051
I have rights!

1097
01:48:04.812 --> 01:48:07.212
<i>- You'd shoot your own people?
- Let us go! People are dying.</i>

1098
01:48:10.213 --> 01:48:11.813
Lyuda! Lyuda!

1099
01:48:17.055 --> 01:48:18.854
Get back I said!

1100
01:48:23.208 --> 01:48:24.456
Everyone calm down!

1101
01:48:26.097 --> 01:48:27.656
Oh. Boris. can we stop for a minute.

1102
01:48:32.098 --> 01:48:35.698
Oh. it smells just like in Odessa.

1103
01:48:36.858 --> 01:48:41.259
Like that time when you strolled up to us
on the beach.

1104
01:48:41.779 --> 01:48:43.938
and you said that you wanted to see

1105
01:48:43.980 --> 01:48:45.779
what I looked like in a bathing suit.

1106
01:48:47.525 --> 01:48:52.460
Sonya. the fish. your parents.
the family ring...

1107
01:48:53.342 --> 01:48:56.221
- the library. Mendel...
- Wait. you remembered the ring?

1108
01:48:56.263 --> 01:48:57.263
Yeah.

1109
01:48:57.742 --> 01:49:00.542
I always knew that someday I'd be
giving it to you.

1110
01:49:01.664 --> 01:49:05.063
You know. I think we'd
have had five children.

1111
01:49:05.224 --> 01:49:07.023
- Oh really Boris. five?
- Yep.

1112
01:49:07.065 --> 01:49:09.864
And Sonya. she... she could have taught
you to cook.

1113
01:49:09.951 --> 01:49:11.611
But I already know how to make pierogi.

1114
01:49:11.653 --> 01:49:14.734
Excellent. Then we could have sat around
a gigantic table. all of us together.

1115
01:49:14.776 --> 01:49:16.708
Yes. every day. Yep. every day.

1116
01:49:16.751 --> 01:49:19.868
Except for the evenings
when we go to the opera.

1117
01:49:20.387 --> 01:49:24.067
No. Boris. I hate the opera. The cinema's
much better.

1118
01:49:24.228 --> 01:49:26.456
- <i>Quickly. it's almost light.</i>
- Be careful!

1119
01:49:27.228 --> 01:49:29.768
Lyuda. hold on to the carpetbag.
All you essentials are there.

1120
01:49:29.810 --> 01:49:31.906
- Hold on to it.
- Boris. what about you?

1121
01:49:31.949 --> 01:49:33.868
<i>Comrade Commander. the boat is
ready to dive.</i>

1122
01:49:34.390 --> 01:49:36.229
I'm travelling on the next steamship.

1123
01:49:36.390 --> 01:49:37.895
I'm an Odessa Jew after all.

1124
01:49:37.937 --> 01:49:41.309
- I'll make it out of here.
- Boris!

1125
01:49:41.351 --> 01:49:44.430
- <i>Ready for emergency dive.</i>
- No. wait.

1126
01:49:45.631 --> 01:49:48.791
Boris! Boris! What did you do?

1127
01:49:49.433 --> 01:49:51.951
Wait. stop.

1128
01:49:51.993 --> 01:49:54.392
I don't want to. Boris!

1129
01:51:56.216 --> 01:52:01.328
<b>Chicago. USA. 1942.</b>

1130
01:53:43.837 --> 01:53:49.077
<b>Moscow. 1957.</b>

1131
01:54:32.230 --> 01:54:35.165
<b>English subtitles translated by
onthemightofprinces</b> <b>For HJ / PTP</b>
